text: Yet another movie about how black Americans are oppressed. I don't get why black actors continue to portray themselves as victims. It's almost as if they don't realize they could be such much more than that on film. I'm sorry, but I'm tired of watching movies with the same, tired, generic, overdone "messages" about something so arbitrary and meaningless as race. They've been doing that whole shtick for a good 6 years now. It's boring, and to be completely honest, most of these "issues" aren't even real issues. The race sentencing gap is anywhere between 5 and 10% (with some research showing it narrows down to 0% if one takes into account criminal history or past offenses). Yes, we all agree in principle it SHOULD be 0%... but meanwhile the *gender* sentencing gap is over 63% and literally not a single soul cares. Hollywood would *NEVER* make a movie about how "men" specifically and generally are oppressed by the court system, because that's not a "progressive" message that people are willing to accept. The fact of the matter is, if a black man is sentenced too harshly, it's not a result of him being black, but rather, the result of him being male. That's a statistically factual, yet no one talks about this honestly... and I'm just tired of the same old "here's another movie about black oppression" game. I can't believe this shit sells. And before anyone tells me "but this is based on REAL events". I know... so explain to me why Hollywood gives absolutely ZERO fucks about the countless of innocent white men being sentenced to death over the last century.

text: I saw this movie. It was great. I loved it. It shows a lot of history from the south. Walter McMillan was innocent. The south was very cruel with blacks in history. There never was any physical evidence that Walter killed that girl. The only evidence against him was that he was last person to have talked with the 18-year-old girl who was killed. But there never was any physical evidence that he did it. The girl's body was bloody all over and her body was dragged around. If Walter would've been the one to do that, there would've been blood on his clothes and on his hands. He was wearing the same clothes all day the day he got arrested. There was no blood on his shirt, his overalls, and his boots, or even his hands. If he had blood in any of his clothes or on his hands, someone would've noticed it. But his kids and some of his neighbors were with him the whole time he spoke with that girl. He wasn't alone with her.
